    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>When Quitting Smoking Proves Too Tough</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Dr Steven A Adelman sympathizes with woman in Nov 19 who cannot stop smoking; says medical professionals underutilize aggressive treatments for nicotine addiction that combine Zyban, nicotine patches and nicotine nasal sprays or inhalers (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Slave of Smoke in an Anti-Smoke Land'' (front page, Nov. 19):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Slave of Smoke in an Anti-Smoke Land'' (front page, Nov. 19):</p>
        <p>As an addiction medicine specialist, I have worked with a number of heroin addicts who have found it much easier to stop using heroin than to quit smoking cigarettes. The agony of profoundly addicted smokers is underestimated by nonsmokers and by former smokers fortunate enough to be less tenaciously addicted to nicotine than others.</p>
        <p>Medical professionals tend to underutilize aggressive treatments for nicotine addiction that combine Zyban, nicotine patches and nicotine nasal sprays or inhalers. Such medically supervised treatments can effectively reduce smoking-related deaths.</p>
        <p>STEVEN A. ADELMAN M.D.  West Roxbury, Mass., Nov. 19, 1998</p>
      </block>
